Introduction ¶

The effectiveness of marketing campaigns is constantly challenged by rapid technological, social and economic changes over the years. Data related with direct marketing campaigns, based on phone calls, of a Portuguese banking institution was obtained from UCI Machine Learning Repository (https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Bank+Marketing). The dataset consists on 41188 observations that present details related to the bank client details, the last contact of the current marketing campaign, details on the contact from previous campaigns, as well as some external social and economic context indicators.

The bank client details include the Age, Occupation, Marital status, Edication level, Default credit status, Housing Loan status, and Personal Loan status. Except for the Age, most of the features related to the clients' details corresponde to categorical values. The information related to the current marketing campaign includes the contact communication type of the call (landline telephone or cellular), the most recent contact month of the year, the week day of the most recent contact, the duration (in seconds) of the call, the number of contacts performed per client, and the number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign. Related to the previous marketing campaigns, the dataset also presents the number of contacts peformed per client on the previous marketing campaign, and the outcome of the previous marketing campaign. The social and economic indicators considered are the Employment Variation Rate (quarterly indicator), the Consumer Price Index (monthly indicator), the Consumer Confidence Index (monthly indicator), the Euribor 3 month rate (daily indicator), and the number of employees (quarterly indicator). All of these rates and indicators are numeric features.

The descriptive features include 10 numeric and 11 categorical features including the target feature y renamed as "Subscribed".

Objectives:¶

Considering the nature of the dataset, the desired target feature identifies whether if a client subscribed or not to a term deposit at the bank. Therefore, the objective of the study is to predict if a client will subscribe (yes or no) to a term deposit.

Drop unnecessary features¶

Still under the Data preparation stage, it will be evaluated the drop of any unnecessary feature from the dataset. Based on the recommendation of the data source, the 'Duration' feature is known to highly affect the output target; if 'Duration'=0 then the target feature is negative. Therefore, 'Duration' should be discarded if the purpose of the study is to obtain a realistic predictive model. (UCI, 2014)

Below, only 'Duration' feature will be dropped from the dataset thus far. Shape and first observations are presented to confirm the correct removal of the column.

Euribor and CPI¶

The current marketing campaign took into account some external economic indices at the time each of the contacts were made. Euribor (Euro Interbank Offered Rate) is a rate of interest used as reference for setting the interest rate on loans. On the other hand, Consumer Price Index (CPI) is an estimate that measures the changes on the price level of representative items.

For this marketing campaign, the Euribor indicator is for a 3 month rate, and the CPI as a monthly indicator. Therefore the limited number of unique values on the rates generates a limited visualisation like the one below. It can be inferred from it that as the Euribor rate remained relatively low (below 2%) the CPI tended to be more evenly distributed. So that a wider variation on the price levels could be expected when the Euribor rate was low.

In [22]:

Consumer Confidence Index and Consumer Price Index¶

The current marketing campaign took into account some external economic indices at the time each of the contacts were made. CCI and CPI are measures of the strength of the economy that can together provide an economic contextfor each of the contacts. The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is an estimate that measures the changes on the price level of representative items. While Consumer Confidence Index (CCI) is a monthly rate that assesses the overall 'health' of the economy.

The plot below displays a negative relation between the CPI and CCI values present in the dataset.The positive values for the CPI suggest positive changes in the price levels, while the low negative values of the CCI indicate a relative weakness on the economic situation. (OECD, 2020)

Machine Learning Data Preparation ¶

Considering the previous Data Preparation and Exploration the following data preprocessing involves the encoding of some features to facilitate the Machine Learning procedures, as well as some scaling

Discretizing Numeric Features: Equal-frequency binning¶

The 'Age' numeric feature will be discretized using equal-frequency binning with 3 bins: namely "young", "middle-aged", and "old". 'Age' will be now a categorical feature after the discretization.

All unique (numeric) values will be firstly identified. Using a quantile-based discretization, these values will be distributed on an equal-frequency binning into the categories previously mentioned.

Making Categorical Features Numeric: Integer Encoding (Ordinal)¶

Considering the nature of some features on the dataset, integer encoding will be applied to ordinal categorical features to preserve the order of the values; namely 'Age' and 'Education'.

A level mapping will be generated for each feature, defining the values according to the desired category order. These later will be replaced for the mapping values, so that instead of labels, 'Age' and 'Education' will now have numeric and ordered values.

Age - Encoding¶

Predictive Modelling: Methodology Overview ¶

To attain the objective of predicting the target feature, the predictive modeling process will be completed in the following order:

It is to be noted that five (5) classifiers were used to predict the target feature

  • K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
  • Decision Tree (DT)
  • Random Forest (RF)
  • Naive Bayes (NB)
  • Support Vector Machine (SVM)
  • First of all, data preparation and transformation were applied to the data prior application of machine learning techniques and classifiers.
    • Target feature was label encoded.
    • One hot encoded categorical features were transformed using Min-Max scaling.
  • It will proceed to perform a Feature Selection, comparing the results of different feature selection methods namely, Full set of Features, F-score, Mutual Information, and Random Forest Importance to evaluate and select the most relevant features from the dataset. To evaluate the performance assessment, a Cross validation of RepeatedStratifiedKFold with stratified 5-fold with 3 repetitions was applied.
  • Afterwards, a data sample of 5000 observations was obtained on the selected best features, in our case using the F-Score 10 selected best features.
  • The data sample with the selected best features from F-Score was split into the data and target features into training and test sets (following a 70-30 proportion).
    • 3500 rows of training data data will be used for hyperparameter tuning phase.
    • 1500 rows of test data will be used for the performance comparison phase.
  • A Cross Validation and Hyperparameter Tuning was performed for the KNN, Decision Tree, Random Forest, Naive Bayes, and Support Vector Machine classifiers. Specifically, cross validation of StratifiedKFold with stratified 5-fold with no repetitions and Grid Search were performed to identify the optimal parameters for each classifier.
    • Stratification ensures that the proportion of the two labels in both train and test sets are the same as the proportion in the full dataset.
    • The area under curve (AUC) is the performance metric.
  • We then proceed to performance comparison, where we fit each tuned classifier with the best set of hyperparameter values on the test data in another cross-validated way to identify which tuned classifier outperforms the others.
    • A 10-fold stratified cross-validation with no repetition with the same seed was applied in each of the classifiers.
    • Both phases involve cross-validation, thus effects of overfitting shall be quite limited.
    • The area under curve (AUC) is also the performance metric.
  • Afterwards, a pairwise t-test was conducted between the AUC score between each of the tuned classifiers to evaluate the statistical significance of their performance.
    • A p-value smaller than 0.05 indicates a statistically significant difference.
  • Lastly, we compare the classifiers with its respective classification reports specifically recall scores and its confusion matrices.

Feature Selection ¶

Before fitting a model, it is good to do feature selection to check whether reducing feature can help achieve better performance. The objective of feature selection is to use a number of features instead of using all features that may lead to poor performance in general.

The feature selection methods that are going to be used are:

  • F-score
  • Mutual Information and
  • Random Forest

All three methods above are the filter methods. The filter methods look at the relationship between each descriptive feature and the target feature using different measures. Using the method, we can check the important features according to the number of features that we are going to select. Lastly, we will compute the average of the performance for each method and make a comparison between all three methods and also the performance with full set features to see which one gives the best performance.

Repeated Startified 5-fold Cross Validation with 3 repetitions ¶

The first thing that needs to be done is defining the wrapper. In this case, we are using the default parameter (n = 5) of nearest neighbour classifier.

Feature Selection Using F-Score ¶

F-Score method is one of the filter feature selection method. This method is going to look at relationship between each descriptive feature with the target feature using F-distribution.

In all of the feature selection methods, we are going to select 10 best features out of the dataset and compare the average performance to see which feature selection gives the best accuracy and whether or not it will improve the performance from when full set features are used.

In [56]:

The methodology of using F-score is:

1) Defining template in SelectKBest

2) Using fit_transform for our data and target

3) Getting scores using scores_ and sorting it from highest to lowest score

import altair as alt

def plot_imp(best_features, scores, method_name, color):
    df = pd.DataFrame({'features': best_features, 'importances': scores})
    chart = alt.Chart(df, width=500,
                      title=method_name + ' Feature Importances'
                     ).mark_bar(opacity=0.75, color=color).encode(
        alt.X('features', title='Feature', sort=None, axis=alt.AxisConfig(labelAngle=45)),
        alt.Y('importances', title='Importance') )
    return chart

Feature Selection Using Random Forest Importance ¶














Random forest importance method is also another filter feature selection method. Random forest consists of decision trees. Each of the decision trees are created using random features and random observations, hence not all the trees see all features or all observations. This will help reduce the risk of over-fitting (The Wisdom of Crowds, 2018).


In classification, impurity is measured using Gini index. While for regression, the measure is measud using residual sum of squared.


When training a tree, how much each feature decreases the impurity can be computed. The more the impurity decreases, the more important the feature is. The average of the decrease of impurity from each feature will then be computed across trees in order to determine the importance of the feature.















In this report, RFI method will be performed using 100 trees as per below.













In [71]:

Cross-Validation and Hyperparameter Tuning ¶














Prior hyperparameter tuning, cross validation was applied. This is mainly because the target lables are imbalanced, with a bigger proportion of no labels than the yes labels, a cross validation using StratifiedKFold function with stratified 5-fold (n_splits = 5) with no repetitions was specifically applied to ensure that the proportion of yes and no labels in both train and test sets are the same as the proportion in the full dataset.















Stratified 5-fold Cross Validation ¶












In [85]:



    


from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold

cv_method = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5,
                            random_state=999)



    















A critical part of machine learning is to find out the "optimal" parameters of the classifier. In order to achieve the optimal parameters, Grid Search was applied for the Hyperparameter Tuning of each of the five classifiers: KNN, DT, NB, RF, and SVM.















K Nearest Neighbor (KNN) Hyperparameter Tuning and Visualization ¶














To optimize the hyperparameters of KNN classifier, the following was indentified to perform GridSearchCV:


    

  • identify the KNN Classifier as an estimator
    • 

  • a dictionary of KNN parameters: number of neighbors or n_neighbors and the distance metric p with 1 (Manhattan), 2 (Euclidean) and 5 (Minkowski)
    • 

  • include the abovementioned cross validation method cv_method
    • 

  • a scoring metric of roc_auc
    • 

  • last step is to fit a KNN model using the training set
    • 














In [86]:



    


from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

knn_classifier = KNeighborsClassifier()

params_KNN = {'n_neighbors': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7], 
              'p': [1, 2, 5]}

gs_KNN = GridSearchCV(estimator= knn_classifier,
                      param_grid=params_KNN, 
                      cv=cv_method,
                      verbose=1,  # verbose: the higher, the more messages
                      scoring='roc_auc', 
                      return_train_score=True)

Model Evaluation: Performance Comparison ¶














Each of the classifiers will now be fitted on the 1500 rows of test data using a 10-fold stratified cross-validation without repetition with the same random state than with which each of the previous three cross-validation runs were applied. By fitting the classifiers in the test data, the performance of each will be measured.


Nonetheless, considering the randomness nature of cross valdation processes, a pairwise t-test will be conducted between the AUC score obtained between each of the tuned classifiers.

print(metrics.confusion_matrix(t_test, t_pred_NB))

Limitations ¶














There are definitely limitations to the modelling strategy that was done above.


The first one is that we can't interpret the reason behind the result from the machine learning system as we focus more on the performance of the prediction. In the future, we could explore further for feature selection as well as the hyperparameter tuning.


The second one is using power transformation only on the training data when hyperparameter tuning was performed on Naive Bayes classifier and ignoring the rest of the dummy data. That might cause the classifier to perform poorly when egvaltuated on test set. A possible solution is to build Naive Bayes on both the numerical and descriptive feature separately. As for the final prediction, it can be computed by multiplying the prediction from each model.


The third limitation is that we did not work with the full dataset in terms of observations. Only 5000 observations were taken to do training and testing. 5000 observations out of 41188 observations is merely slightly over 10% of the original dataset, which more or less will definitely affect the result. Without the limitation of the run time, we could try to use all of the observations for training and testing.


Through model evaluation results, we can see some classifier outperforms other classifiers. In this case, we can improve on the parameter tuning to cover more parameters instead of just a subset of all the parameters. For example, we found that Decision Tree is performing better than the rest of the classifier. Instead of just exploring criterion, max_depth and min_samples_split, we could also explore other parameters like max_features, max_leaf_nodes, min_impurity_decrease and many more.















Summary and Conclusions ¶














Summary and Conclusions
In this report, the goal was to predict whether the client will subscribe to a term deposit. We started with data preprocessing to clean the data. Data exploration was then done with visualizations to understand the data better.


Feature selection was performed next and 10 number of features were selected. In feature selection, we went through the filter methods and found that using just 10 features most of the time gives a better performance compared to using full set of features. In feature selection, F-Score feature selection method gives the best performance compared to the rest of the method and full set of features.


Using the 10 best features, the report proceed to hyperparameter tuning. The objective of doing hyperparameter tuning is to get the most optimal parameter in different classifiers. The classifiers that we used for comparison are K-Nearest Neighbor, Decision Tree, Random Forest, Naive Bayes and SVM.


After hyperparameter tuning, the report proceed on to model evaluation. In this part, we did performance comparison by fitting the test set on the classifiers and compared the average result. At this point we found that Random Forest gave the best performance according to the 10-fold AUC score. In classification report, we chose to use recall / TPR to detect whether the client will subscribe to a term deposit. In this case, Random Forest classifier together with Decision Tree classifier gives the best recall score for client who subscribed to term deposit. The confusion matrix results show the details of the prediction and are in line with the classification report as Decision Tree classifier has the highest True Positive followed by Random Forest classifier.
